Thinking a lot lately about how diet culture and western beauty standards consistently force women to not only despise their bodies and want to change even the smallest details about them, but also force women into thinking that is all they are defined by. All the while, bodies like ours are revered in the most renowned museums and history books, as art. 
Somehow patriarchal standards have continued to make women feel like we are competing against each other, ourselves and our own self image. Imagine looking at a beautiful sculpture in a museum and thinking “she would’ve looked better with xyz”. 
You wouldn’t, so why would we think that of ourselves? As I’ve gained weight people have asked me how I’ve dealt with it and the reality is, thin, fat, or otherwise my body will always be art. My body and beauty isn’t currency in which i have to pay to be respected in the world. I do not have to show up as perfect to be worthy. My body is art, it helps tell my story, but doesn’t define it.
Home on the range or whatever!!!

Healthy hair starts with a healthy scalp, but what happens after you’ve grown new hair? Pre shampoo oil treatments are a game changer for my people who are wanting to grow long healthy hair because they help with length retention. You may be able to grow your hair, but if you’re not properly taking care of it, you’ll experience breakage which some can confuse with hair LOSS. Lots of things contribute to breakage like heat styling and chemical processing, but water can also in some ways be damaging.  I’ll be doing a longer explainer on hygral fatigue, what to look for and what is actually cause for concern. 
Until then, using a pre wash oil treatment on your lengths is a great option. 
 
Products i used here: @theordinary peptide density serum for my scalp 
@mielleorganics rosemary strength oil mixed with a couple drops of @virtuelabs healing oil on my lengths

I’m still here 💜 and for the record I miss being able to talk/post about my body without it constantly being co-opted by men. 
I don’t even get to enjoy the body I fought so hard to value and love. 
It’s my home and I don’t even get to enjoy her because men don’t have the mental depth or emotional intelligence to see women as more than just objects of pleasure. Bodies are not inherently sexual as they are simply just bodies. I’d like to be able to enjoy mine again without the scrutiny and over sexualization of men. 

I wish I could take ownership of my body again without the constant peanut gallery of incels, misogynists, etc making commentary and then of course posting my body to be ogled at on all kinds of platforms I didn’t consent to being on. Because at the end of the day it’s simple, people get off on taking away your autonomy. It’s all about taking away your power. And then in the magic of being a woman-you are blamed. It’s your fault, for simply existing. 

This is trivial in comparison to some of the horrendous violence and oppression women face globally, but it’s all a microcosm of the same bigger issue. 

We deserve the simplicity of existing freely.
